<h2 id="what-to-eat">What to eat (and what it costs)</h2>
<p>The food is the real reason to come. Across all these markets the prices are remarkably consistent, and they're cheap: a satisfying market dinner of three or four dishes runs ฿120–250 a head. These are the things I order on repeat.</p>
<p>Start with <strong>moo ping</strong> (grilled pork skewers, ฿10–15 each) and <strong>sticky rice</strong> in a bag for ฿10. <strong>Som tam</strong> (green papaya salad, ฿40–60) is everywhere — say "mai phet" if you can't handle heat, because vendors here don't tone it down for tourists. <strong>Grilled squid</strong> and prawns are sold by weight, usually ฿60–150 a portion, and a whole grilled fish runs ฿120–250. For dessert, <strong>mango sticky rice</strong> is ฿50–80 and fresh fruit shakes are ฿40–60.</p>
<p>One honest warning: hygiene varies. Stick to stalls with a queue and high turnover, watch that grilled food is cooked through, and you'll be fine — that's how the locals eat every night.</p>
<div class="callout tip">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-info"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>Local tip</h4><p>Eat where the Thai families queue, not where the photos of food are biggest. The stalls with picture menus and English-only signage are usually 30–50% pricier for worse food. The best plate I had this year was ฿50 pad see ew from a cart on Soi Buakhao with no menu at all.</p></div>
</div>
<h2 id="what-to-buy">What to buy &amp; how to bargain</h2>
<p>Beyond food, the markets are a souvenir and clothing goldmine if you bargain. The unwritten rule: the first price quoted to a foreigner is inflated <strong>30–50%</strong>. Smile, offer about half, settle somewhere in the middle, and be ready to walk away — that's when the real price appears.</p>
<p>Worth buying: <strong>elephant-print trousers</strong> (฿150–250), <strong>linen shirts</strong> (฿200–400), <strong>fake-brand T-shirts</strong> (฿100–200), <strong>silk-look scarves</strong>, leather sandals, phone cases and Bluetooth gadgets (test before you pay), and Thai snacks like dried mango and roasted cashews to take home. M.I.T. and the Night Bazaar are best for clothes and gadgets; Thepprasit is best for cheap basics in bulk.</p>
<p>Skip the "designer" watches and electronics with brand logos — they're knock-offs that rarely last, and customs can be an issue back home. For real handicrafts and Thai goods, you'll do better at the <a class="inline" href="blog-sanctuary-of-truth-pattaya.html">Sanctuary of Truth</a> gift shops, but the markets win on price for everyday souvenirs.</p>
<div class="callout warn">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-scam-alert"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>What to avoid</h4><p>Watch for the "tester" gadget that works and the boxed one that doesn't — always open and test electronics before paying. Avoid pre-cut fruit left in the sun, and don't take the first songthaew driver who offers a "special market price" — a normal shared ride is ฿10–30, not ฿200.</p></div>
</div>
<h2 id="by-area">Night markets by area</h2>
<p>Where you're staying decides which markets are realistically walkable. Here's the quick playbook by neighbourhood.</p>
<div class="hood">
<div class="row"><div class="area">Central Pattaya</div><div class="desc">Pattaya Night Bazaar, M.I.T. and the Soi Buakhao food strip are all walkable. Best base if you want a market every night without transport.</div></div>
<div class="row"><div class="area">South Pattaya / Pratumnak</div><div class="desc">Closest to Thepprasit Market (Fri–Sun) — a ฿10–30 songthaew or short Grab ride. Quieter hotels, weekend-market access.</div></div>
<div class="row"><div class="area">Jomtien</div><div class="desc">Beachfront evening stalls on your doorstep; Thepprasit is a 10-minute hop north. Good for sea-view snacking.</div></div>
<div class="row"><div class="area">Naklua / Wong Amat</div><div class="desc">Naklua Market and the Lan Po seafood stalls are local and calm. Further from the big tourist bazaars but the most authentic food.</div></div>
</div>
<h2 id="costs">What a night out costs</h2>
<p>Night markets are one of the cheapest evenings out in Pattaya. Here's roughly what to budget per person for a typical market night in 2026 — dinner, a couple of drinks, and a bit of shopping.</p>
<div class="money-grid">
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Street-food dinner</div><div class="val">฿120–250</div><p>Three or four dishes plus dessert. Cheaper at Thepprasit and Soi Buakhao, pricier at tourist bazaars.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Drinks</div><div class="val">฿40–110</div><p>Fresh fruit shake ฿40–60; large local beer ฿60–110. Bring cash — many stalls don't take cards.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Songthaew there &amp; back</div><div class="val">฿20–60</div><p>Shared baht-bus rides ฿10–30 each way on main routes. Agree nothing extra; don't accept ฿200 "tourist" quotes.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Souvenirs / clothes</div><div class="val">฿150–600</div><p>After bargaining. Trousers ฿150–250, shirts ฿200–400. Skip if you're just there to eat.</p></div>
</div>
<p>All in, a relaxed market evening with dinner, drinks and a little shopping comes to roughly <strong>฿300–800 per person</strong> — less if you stick to Thepprasit and Soi Buakhao. For more on stretching your baht across a whole trip, see how it adds up in our wider <a class="inline" href="pillar-eat-drinks.html">eating &amp; drinking guide</a>.</p>
<!-- FAQ -->
<h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq">
<div class="faq-item open">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">Which is the best night market in Pattaya? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">Thepprasit Market is the best overall — it's the biggest, cheapest and most local, packed with both street food and clothing. The catch is it only fully opens Friday to Sunday, roughly 5pm–11pm. If you need somewhere open every night, the Pattaya Night Bazaar on Second Road is the most convenient central alternative.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">What nights is Thepprasit Market open? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">Thepprasit Market runs on Friday, Saturday and Sunday evenings, from about 5pm until 11pm, with the food and clothing sections busiest from 7pm. It's closed Monday to Thursday, so plan your visit for the weekend. Arrive by 6:30pm to beat the worst of the crowds and the heat.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">How much does a meal cost at a Pattaya night market? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">Cheap. Grilled pork skewers are ฿10–15 each, som tam is ฿40–60, grilled squid or prawns ฿60–150, and mango sticky rice ฿50–80. A full street-food dinner of three or four dishes runs about ฿120–250 per person — far less than a sit-down restaurant. Bring cash, as most stalls don't take cards.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">Can you bargain at Pattaya night markets? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">Yes, and you should on clothing, souvenirs and gadgets — opening prices for foreigners are inflated 30–50%. Offer about half, settle in the middle, and be willing to walk away to get the real price. Food prices, however, are usually fixed and fair, so don't haggle over a ฿50 plate.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">What's the best night market for shopping rather than food? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">Made in Thailand Market (M.I.T.) and the Pattaya Night Bazaar, both on Second Road, are best for shopping — clothes, gadgets, leather goods and souvenirs, open nightly. Thepprasit is cheapest for clothing in bulk but weekend-only. Bargain hard at all three; M.I.T. has the most inflated opening prices.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">Are Pattaya night markets safe and hygienic? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">They're generally safe and busy. For food hygiene, stick to stalls with a queue and high turnover, make sure grilled items are cooked through, and avoid pre-cut fruit sitting in the sun. Keep an eye on your bag in crowds, test any electronics before paying, and use shared ฿10–30 songthaews rather than overpriced private quotes.</div></div>
</div>
</div>
<p style="margin-top:var(--s5)">So if you want one answer: go to <strong>Thepprasit Market on a Friday or Saturday night</strong> for the full experience, fall back on the <strong>Pattaya Night Bazaar</strong> any other night, and eat your way along <strong>Soi Buakhao</strong> when you just want cheap, brilliant street food. Bring cash, bargain on everything that isn't food, and follow the queues. Next, plan where to base yourself with our <a class="inline" href="blog-where-to-stay-in-pattaya.html">where to stay in Go To Pattaya</a>, or dig into the dishes themselves in our <a class="inline" href="blog-street-food-pattaya.html">Pattaya street food guide</a>.</p>
