<p>The ฿1,000 gap between our ฿14,000 core spend and the ฿15,000 ceiling is your real-world cushion. We've come in at ฿13,800 in cheap weeks and ฿14,800 with one bigger splurge — both comfortably inside the line.</p>
<!-- WHERE TO STAY -->
<h2 id="where-to-stay">Where to sleep cheap — real places, real prices</h2>
<figure class="art-img">
<img alt="Pattaya budget 7 days 3 in Pattaya, Thailand" height="428" loading="lazy" src="../Pattaya-Tum-Gorseller-Resized/pattaya-budget-7-days-3.webp" width="760"/>
<figcaption>Pattaya Budget 7 Days 3 – explore Pattaya's best spots</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Skip Beach Road resorts entirely. The cheap stays cluster in three pockets: <strong>Soi Buakhao</strong> (central but inland, best for food and nightlife), <strong>Pratumnak Hill</strong> (quieter, walkable to Cosy Beach) and <strong>Jomtien Second Road</strong> (further south, calmer beach). All five picks below sit in those zones — for the full area-by-area rundown see our <a class="inline" href="blog-where-to-stay-in-pattaya.html">where to stay in Pattaya</a> guide.</p>
<div class="hood">
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-stay"></use></svg> Lub d Jomtien · ฿500</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Polished hostel chain with a pool and female-only dorm.</b> Six-bed A/C dorm, breakfast included, five minutes' walk to Jomtien beach. The comfortable end of the budget — book it for your last couple of nights.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-stay"></use></svg> MD Hostel · ฿350</div>
<div class="desc"><b>The cheapest reputable bed in the centre.</b> Bunks have privacy curtains, a plug and a light per bed; it's two minutes from Thepprasit Market on Soi Buakhao. The street is loud — bring earplugs — but nothing beats the price.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-stay"></use></svg> Hi-In Sukhumvit · ฿400</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Newer build, female-only dorm, rooftop terrace.</b> Slightly inland from Pattaya Beach but walkable (about eight minutes to Beach Road) and the best WiFi in this price range.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-stay"></use></svg> Off-season hotel double · ฿650</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Two travellers split a private hotel double for less per head than a dorm.</b> Days Inn or Sunshine Vista on Soi 13 / Second Road include a pool, A/C and breakfast. Look May–October only — ฿650 twin = ฿325 each.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-stay"></use></svg> Long-stay Airbnb · ฿300</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Stay 14+ nights and monthly-rate apartments hit ฿9,000 a month.</b> That works out to ฿300 a night for a Pratumnak Hill or View Talay condo with a kitchen, A/C, washing machine and pool building.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>For a seven-day budget the math is simple: <strong>MD Hostel × 5 nights + Lub d × 2 nights = ฿2,750.</strong> That leaves ฿750 in the sleep column for a single private-room splurge mid-week, if your back can't take another night on a dorm mattress.</p>
<div class="callout">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-info"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>Don't book all 7 nights in advance</h4><p>Walk-in rates after 2 PM in low season run 15–25% below Booking.com. We routinely get ฿350 dorm beds down to ฿280 in person. Book the first two nights online for security, then walk the next five.</p></div>
</div>
<!-- EAT CHEAP -->
<h2 id="eat-cheap">Eat for ฿100–200 a meal — where locals eat</h2>
<p>Pattaya is one of the cheapest cities in Southeast Asia to eat in, as long as you ignore the Beach Road menus and walk one block inland. <strong>Pad thai for ฿80, a full rice plate for ฿70, a bowl of boat noodles for ฿50.</strong> Three meals a day at ฿250 total is genuinely doable — and the food is hot, fresh and aimed at Thais, not tourists. A rough per-tier guide for 2026:</p>
<div class="money-grid">
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">7-Eleven survival</div><div class="val">฿55</div><p>Toastie ฿35, coffee ฿25, cup noodles ฿20 — a fast cheap meal between activities. 400+ branches citywide.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Soi Buakhao stalls</div><div class="val">฿60</div><p>Khao kha moo (braised pork rice) ฿50, som tam ฿60, sticky rice + grilled pork ฿80. Open all day.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Thepprasit Night Market</div><div class="val">฿80</div><p>The best ฿80 pad thai in town, mango sticky rice ฿60, whole grilled chicken ฿100. Tue/Wed/Fri/Sat/Sun, 5 PM–midnight.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Lan Po Park seafood</div><div class="val">฿150</div><p>Weekend Naklua market — whole steamed sea bass ฿250, grilled prawns ฿200/kg, eaten by the water.</p></div>
</div>
<p>A working pattern: <strong>7-Eleven breakfast (฿60) + Thai canteen lunch (฿70) + night-market dinner (฿120) = ฿250 a day.</strong> Repeated seven days that's ฿1,750, exactly on budget. Add a coffee-shop iced latte (฿60) and a 7-Eleven beer (฿55) and you're at ฿365 a day for food and drinks — still under. The Pattaya Floating Market food court is the one tourist spot worth a stop: boat noodles ฿50 and coconut ice cream ฿40 at real prices on the back deck.</p>
<!-- FREE AND PAID -->
<h2 id="free-and-paid">Free &amp; paid things to do</h2>
<p>Here's the secret that keeps the budget intact: most of Pattaya's best days don't cost anything. If you did one free thing per day across the week you'd still have plenty left over. Start with these.</p>
<div class="cat-grid">
<div class="cat-card">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-24"><use href="#pg-beach"></use></svg></div>
<div><div class="label">Free · beach</div><b>Jomtien Beach, south end</b><p>Two free hours of swim and sand, far less crowded than Pattaya Beach.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="cat-card">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-24"><use href="#pg-attractions"></use></svg></div>
<div><div class="label">Free · viewpoint</div><b>Khao Phra Tamnak</b><p>The big golden Buddha hill — free entry and a 360° view over the whole bay.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="cat-card">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-24"><use href="#pg-attractions"></use></svg></div>
<div><div class="label">Free · landmark</div><b>Buddha Mountain (Khao Chi Chan)</b><p>A 130m Buddha laser-etched into a cliff. Free entry; share a songthaew with backpackers.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="cat-card">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-24"><use href="#pg-anchor"></use></svg></div>
<div><div class="label">Free · sunrise</div><b>Bali Hai Pier at dawn</b><p>5:30–6:30 AM, fishing boats coming in — the quietest, prettiest hour in Pattaya.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="cat-card">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-24"><use href="#pg-wellness"></use></svg></div>
<div><div class="label">Free · temples</div><b>Wat Yansangwararam &amp; Lan Po Park</b><p>Free entry to the temple complex and pagoda hill, plus a sunset boardwalk and swing in Naklua.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="cat-card">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-24"><use href="#pg-air-con"></use></svg></div>
<div><div class="label">Free · cooldown</div><b>Central Festival mall</b><p>Free midday A/C and WiFi when the heat peaks — window-shop, recharge, move on.</p></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Once you've worked through the free list, these are the paid activities that earn their keep. Each is verified at the listed price as of May 2026. Doing everything on this list would cost ฿5,800 — well over budget — so you'll pick four or five.</p>
<div class="hood">
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-attractions"></use></svg> ฿500 · Sanctuary of Truth</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Pattaya's #1 sight.</b> The all-wood carved temple, ฿500 foreigner entry, worth every baht. Spend two hours.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-ferry"></use></svg> ฿400 · Koh Larn day</div>
<div class="desc"><b>The classic budget day trip.</b> Ferry round-trip ฿60 from Bali Hai, beach chair ฿100, lunch ฿200, island songthaew ฿40 — a full day for ฿400.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-eat"></use></svg> ฿450 · Thai cooking class</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Bua Thai Cooking School, Soi Buakhao.</b> Morning class for ฿450 — three dishes, a market tour and a recipe book. You eat what you cook.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-massage"></use></svg> ฿200 · Thai massage</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Skip the ฿400 Beach Road shops.</b> A proper hour-long Thai massage in Soi Buakhao or Soi 13 is ฿200, same skill, half the price.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-discount"></use></svg> ฿500 · Underwater World</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Go on the discount day.</b> Normal entry ฿900, but the Tuesday combo brings the walk-through aquarium tunnel down to ฿500.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-tours"></use></svg> ฿2,500 · Paramotor flight</div>
<div class="desc"><b>The one big-ticket item we'd book.</b> A 15-minute tandem flight over Pattaya Bay with GoPro footage — the splurge that earns its keep.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The realistic mix: Sanctuary of Truth + Koh Larn + cooking class + two massages + one splurge = about ฿4,000, or ฿570 a day across the week. Pair the paid days with the free ones and you stay comfortably inside budget. For the full menu of options at every price tier, browse our <a class="inline" href="plan-my-trip.html">plan-your-trip hub</a>.</p>
<!-- GETTING AROUND -->
<h2 id="getting-around">Getting around for ฿20 — never Grab the short trips</h2>
<p>Pattaya's transport economy has one big secret: the <strong>baht bus (songthaew)</strong> — blue pickup trucks with bench seats in the back. You wave, they stop, you climb in, you ring the bell, and you pay ฿20 (sometimes ฿30 as a foreigner). They run set loops along Beach Road, Second Road, Sukhumvit, Pattaya Klang and Thepprasit, dense enough that 90% of trips inside the city cost ฿20.</p>
