<div class="cmp-hint">← swipe to see all columns →</div>
<div class="compare-foot">Prices verified May 2026. Baht-bus fares are the standard ฿20 local rate; foreigners are sometimes quoted ฿30.</div>
</div>
<p><strong>The rule:</strong> if a baht bus goes there, take the baht bus. Grab only makes sense after 1 AM (when songthaews thin out) or with heavy luggage. We've spent ฿560 across full weeks riding baht buses exclusively — that's 28 rides. A scooter at ฿200 a day only pays off if you'd ride more than five baht buses in a day, which most travellers don't.</p>
<div class="callout warn">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-warning"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>Scooter warning</h4><p>Pattaya scooter rental is cheap but accident rates are very high. Bring an international driving permit, wear a helmet every time, and check that your travel insurance actually covers motorbikes — most don't. If you've never ridden, this is not the city to learn. Stick with baht buses.</p></div>
</div>
<!-- DAY BY DAY -->
<h2 id="day-by-day">The 7-day itinerary, day by day</h2>
<p>Here's the actual plan I'd send a friend, with each day's running total. The week comes to <strong>฿13,140</strong> — comfortably under ฿15,000, with ฿1,860 left over for whatever surprises you. The splurge lands on day 4, by which point enough cheap days have stacked up that the contrast really hits.</p>
<div class="hood">
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-sun"></use></svg> Day 1 · Mon · ฿1,640</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Arrival + setup.</b> Bell 389 bus from Suvarnabhumi (฿130), check into MD Hostel, Beach Road walk and a 7-Eleven lunch, Soi Buakhao stall dinner, look-only Walking Street stroll. One-off costs: DTAC tourist SIM ฿299 and one ฿220 ATM withdrawal.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-attractions"></use></svg> Day 2 · Tue · ฿1,150</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Viewpoint + Sanctuary of Truth.</b> Free Khao Phra Tamnak hike, Pratumnak canteen lunch (฿80), Sanctuary of Truth (฿500 + baht bus), then Thepprasit Night Market dinner — pad thai, mango sticky rice and a Leo for ฿220.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-ferry"></use></svg> Day 3 · Wed · ฿1,090</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Koh Larn day trip.</b> 8 AM ferry from Bali Hai (฿60 return), songthaew to quieter Samae Beach (฿80), chair + seafood fried rice (฿280), swim, last ferry back at 6 PM, Soi Buakhao dinner. Add sunscreen from Big C (฿120).</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-tours"></use></svg> Day 4 · Thu · ฿3,210</div>
<div class="desc"><b>The splurge.</b> Paramotor flight over Pattaya Bay (฿2,500, GoPro included), cheap post-adrenaline noodles, free Lan Po Park boardwalk, then a seafood-by-weight dinner — whole grilled sea bass ฿250 plus sides and a Leo.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-eat"></use></svg> Day 5 · Fri · ฿1,470</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Cook, soak, sightsee.</b> Bua Thai cooking class (฿450, you eat your three dishes), Pattaya Floating Market (฿300 with snacks), a ฿200 Soi 13 Thai massage, then a Friday Thepprasit market dinner.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-attractions"></use></svg> Day 6 · Sat · ฿1,470</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Jomtien switch.</b> Move to Lub d Jomtien (฿500, breakfast included), share a songthaew to Buddha Mountain (฿200), free Wat Yansangwararam visit, Jomtien beach swim, beachfront walk, hostel-bar Leos and ฿150 laundry.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-anchor"></use></svg> Day 7 · Sun · ฿1,110</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Slow last day.</b> Bali Hai sunrise walk with a 7-Eleven coffee, free Lub d breakfast, the Sunday-only Lan Po seafood market, a last Thai massage and mall A/C, then a final Soi Buakhao street feast.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="compare-wrap">
